\begin_layout Plain Layout
1.
 The general expression for the average dipole moment is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mu\right\rangle =\frac{\int_{0}^{\pi}A\mathrm{exp}(\frac{\mu\varepsilon\cos\theta}{kT})(\mu\cos\theta)2\pi\sin\theta d\theta}{\int_{0}^{\pi}A\exp(\frac{\mu\varepsilon\cos\theta}{kT})2\pi\sin\theta d\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Let
\begin_inset Formula $x=\cos\theta$
\end_inset

 and let
\begin_inset Formula $a=\mu\varepsilon/kT$
\end_inset

.
 Making this substitution, Eqn.
 1 can be rewritten as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mu\right\rangle =\mu\frac{\int_{-1}^{1}xe^{ax}dx}{\int_{-1}^{1}e^{ax}dx}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We first consider the integral in the numerator of Eqn.
 2.
 From integral tables,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-1}^{1}xe^{\alpha x}dx=\left.\frac{e^{\alpha x}(ax-1)}{a^{2}}\right|_{-1}^{1}=\frac{(a-1)e^{a}+(a+1)e^{-a}}{a^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Next, we consider the integral in the denominator of Eqn.
 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-1}^{1}xe^{ax}dx=\left.\frac{1}{a}e^{ax}\right|_{-1}^{1}=\frac{1}{a}(e^{a}-e^{-a})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Combining Eqn.
 3 and 4 into Eqn.
 2,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mu\right\rangle =\frac{(a-1)e^{a}+(a+1)e^{-a}}{a^{2}}\cdotp\frac{a}{e^{a}-e^{-a}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $=\frac{a(e^{a}+e^{-a})+e^{-a}-e^{a}}{a(e^{a}-e^{-a})}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Grouping terms together,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mu\right\rangle =\frac{e^{a}+e^{-a}}{e^{a}-e^{-a}}+\frac{e^{-a}-e^{a}}{a(e^{a}-e^{-a})}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\mbox{\ensuremath{\left\langle \mu\right\rangle =\mathrm{coth}a-\frac{1}{a}}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
2.
 The dipole moment is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=P_{s}\cdotp$
\end_inset

(volume of unit cell)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For the cubic phase of lead titanate, the unit cell volume is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $V=(4.1\,\mathrm{x}\,10^{-10}\mathrm{m)^{3}=68.92\,\mathrm{x\,10^{-31}m^{3}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The dipole moment is then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=(0.8\,\mathrm{C/m^{2})}\cdotp(68.92\,\mathrm{x}\,10^{-31}\mathrm{m^{3})}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\mu=5.51\,\mathrm{x}\,10^{-29}\mathrm{C}\cdotp\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
3.
 The polarizability is given generally as (see slide 117)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $P=N_{m}\mu$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where
\begin_inset Formula $N_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the number of molecules per unit volume and
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

is the dipole moment.
 The dipole moment between two charges of
\begin_inset Formula $+q$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $-q$
\end_inset

 seperated by a distance
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=q\delta$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The polarization
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is then
\begin_inset Formula $P=N_{m}q\delta$
\end_inset

.
 For the case of an Ar atom,
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the displacement of the 8 valence electrons from the net positive core
 (nucleus plus inner electrons) of the atom, which can be approximated as
 the atomic radius.
 To calculate
\begin_inset Formula $N_{m},$
\end_inset

 we consider Ar as an ideal gas at room temperature and 1 atmosphere.
 The number of Ar atoms is then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $N_{m}=\frac{\mathrm{mol}}{24.5\,\mathrm{L}}\cdotp\frac{6.02\,\mathrm{x\,10^{23}atoms}}{\mathrm{mol}}\cdotp\frac{1\,\mathrm{L}}{\mathrm{dm^{3}}}\cdotp\frac{10^{3}\mathrm{dm^{3}}}{\mathrm{m}}=2.46\,\mathrm{x\,10^{25}}\mathrm{atoms/m^{3}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The polarization is then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $P=(2.46\,\mathrm{x\,10^{25}atoms})\cdotp(8\cdotp1.602\,\mathrm{x}\,10^{-19}\mathrm{C})\cdot(0.15\,\mathrm{x}\,10^{-9}\mathrm{m})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{P=4.7\,\mathrm{x\,10^{-3}C/m^{2}=4.7\,\mathrm{x}\,10^{-7}C/cm^{2}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
4.
 This problem is similar to that worked out in the slides (see slides 128-131)
 for the case of a simple harmonic oscillator without the damping term.
 The approach to calculating the frequency dependent polarizability from
 the equation of motion is summarized as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(a) Calculate the frequency dependent displacement (
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(b) Calculate the dipole moment
\begin_inset Formula $mu_{0}=-ex_{0}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the fundamental charge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(c) Calculate the polarizability
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\mu_{0}/\varepsilon_{loc}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To solve for the frequency response of
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

, we first write
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 in terms of its Fourier transform, that is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dt\,x\,(\omega)e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The equation of motion is now
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $m\frac{d^{2}}{dt^{2}}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x(\omega)e^{-i\omega t}dt+b\frac{d}{dt}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x(\omega)e^{i\omega t}dt+m\omega_{0}^{2}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x(\omega)e^{i\omega t}dt=-e\varepsilon_{loc}\sin\omega t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The order in which we perform the integration and derivatives with respect
 to time does not matter.
 Taking the derivatives with respect to time first,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $-m\omega^{2}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x(\omega)e^{-i\omega t}dt-ib\omega\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x(\omega)e^{-i\omega t}dt+m\omega_{0}^{2}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}x(\omega)e^{-i\omega t}dt=-e\varepsilon_{loc}\sin\omega t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here, we note that the above equation is an
\begin_inset Formula $ordinary,\,linear$
\end_inset

 differential equation in terms of the variable
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 By
\begin_inset Formula $ordinary$
\end_inset

, we mean that there is only one variable,
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 By
\begin_inset Formula $linear,$
\end_inset

 we mean that only terms first order in
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are present.
 The equation would be nonlinear if, for example, the acceleration term
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}x/dt^{2}$
\end_inset

 was replaced by
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}(x^{2})/dt^{2}$
\end_inset

 or if the restoration force
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}^{2}x$
\end_inset

 was replaced with
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}^{2}e^{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The reason that we stress that this is a linear differential equation is
 because, as a linear equation, we should expect a linear response of
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with respect to the input.
 That is, if the electrons are being driven by a field that is sinusoidal
 with time, then their motion will be sinusoidal with time.
 This does not mean, however, that the motion will be
\begin_inset Formula $in\,phase$
\end_inset

 with the applied field; the motion may follow the applied field with some
 delay (it can never be
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ahead
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the field; that is not physical!).
 We will see in this case that the damping term causes a phase delay in
 the response.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
With this intuition, we expect the solution for
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 to be of the form
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)=x_{0}\sin\omega t$
\end_inset

 (note that neglecting the phase here means that it will come up in the
 solution for
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

).
 According to Eqn.
 5, we can then write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)=x_{0}\sin\omega t=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dt\,x(\omega)e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
which means that the equation of motion is now
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $-m\omega^{2}x_{0}\sin\omega t-in\omega x_{0}\sin\omega t+m\omega_{0}^{2}x_{0}\sin\omega t=-e\varepsilon_{loc}\sin\omega t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\sin\omega t(m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2}-ib\omega)=-e\varepsilon_{loc}\sin\omega t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dividing by sin
\begin_inset Formula $\omega t$
\end_inset

 and solving for
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=-\frac{e\varepsilon_{loc}}{m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2}-ib\omega}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that there is an imaginary term in the denominator; this contributes
 to the phase lag.
 Next, we calculate the dipole moment:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}=-ex_{0}=\frac{e^{2}\varepsilon_{loc}}{m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2}-ib\omega}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The polarizability is
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\mu_{0}/\varepsilon_{loc}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\alpha=\frac{e^{2}}{m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2}-ib\omega}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In order to examine graphically the frequency response of the polarizability,
 it is useful to obtain the magnitude and phase of
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we need to first write
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a complex number of the form
\begin_inset Formula $a+ib$
\end_inset

.
 The magnitude
\begin_inset Formula $M(\omega)$
\end_inset

 is then
\begin_inset Formula $M=\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and the phase lag is
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=-\arctan(b/a).$
\end_inset

 Multiplying
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 by its complex conjugate,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\frac{e^{2}}{m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2}-ib\omega}\cdotp\frac{m\omega_{0}^{2}+m\omega^{2}+ib\omega}{m\omega_{0}^{2}+m\omega^{2}+ib\omega}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\frac{e^{2}(m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2}+ib\omega)}{(m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2})^{2}+b^{2}\omega^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\frac{e^{2}(m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2})}{(m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2})^{2}+b^{2}\omega^{2}}+i\frac{e^{2}b\omega}{(m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2})^{2}+b^{2}\omega^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The magnitude is then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $M(\omega)=\left[\left(\frac{e^{2}(m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2})}{(m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2})^{2}+b^{2}\omega^{2}}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{e^{2}b\omega}{(m\omega_{0}^{2}-m\omega^{2})^{2}+b^{2}\omega^{2}}\right)^{2}\right]^{1/2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and the phase is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\omega)=\arctan\left(\frac{b\omega}{m\omega^{2}-m\omega_{0}^{2}}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The magnitude and phase lag are plotted in Fig.
 1.
 With these equations, we now consider the magnitude and phase at several
 points of interest.
 We note the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At low frequencies, the magnitude approaches a finite number,
\begin_inset Formula $e^{2}/(m\omega_{0}^{2}),$
\end_inset

 and the phase lag approaches 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At high frequencies, the magnitude approaches zero and the phase lag approaches
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At the resonant condition
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, the magnitude attains its largest value and the phase lag is equal to
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

